  "footnotes": [
    "Northwest: Kurdish Autonomous Region (Dohuk, Erbil, Sulaymaniyah, Halabja) + Nineveh, Kirkuk, Salah al-Din — the ancient Assyrian heartland and Kurdish highlands; Shanidar Cave here contains the oldest known Neanderthal burial site",
    "Southwest: Anbar governorate — the western Euphrates corridor; historically the main route between Mesopotamia, the Levant, and Arabia; site of Fallujah and Ramadi",
    "Central: Baghdad, Diyala, Babil, Karbala, Najaf, Wasit — the Babylonian heartland; Ctesiphon (Sassanid/Parthian capital) and later Baghdad (Abbasid capital, founded 762) are both here",
    "Southeast: Basra, Dhi Qar, Muthanna, Qadisiyyah, Maysan — the original Sumerian heartland (Ur, Eridu, Lagash, Uruk) and the Persian Gulf port zone; al-Hira (Lakhmid capital) was near Kufa",
    "The Sack of Baghdad (1258): Mongol Il-Khan Hülegü destroyed the Abbasid capital and killed the last caliph al-Musta'sim, ending the Islamic Golden Age and causing catastrophic demographic collapse in Iraq"
  ]
}
